   367‚Üí    format: str,
   368‚Üí) -> tuple[float, float]:
   369‚Üí    """Divide `value` by `divisor`, returning the quotient and remainder.
   370‚Üí
   371‚Üí    If `unit` is `minimum_unit`, the quotient will be the rounding of `value / divisor`
   372‚Üí    according to the `format` string and the remainder will be zero. The rationale is
   373‚Üí    that if `unit` is the unit of the quotient, we cannot represent the remainder
   374‚Üí    because it would require a unit smaller than the `minimum_unit`.
   375‚Üí
   376‚Üí    >>> from humanize.time import _quotient_and_remainder, Unit
   377‚Üí    >>> _quotient_and_remainder(36, 24, Unit.DAYS, Unit.DAYS, [], "%0.2f")
   378‚Üí    (1.5, 0)
   379‚Üí
   380‚Üí    If `unit` is in `suppress`, the quotient will be zero and the remainder will be the
   381‚Üí    initial value. The idea is that if we cannot use `unit`, we are forced to use a
   382‚Üí    lower unit, so we cannot do the division.
   383‚Üí
   384‚Üí    >>> _quotient_and_remainder(36, 24, Unit.DAYS, Unit.HOURS, [Unit.DAYS], "%0.2f")
   385‚Üí    (0, 36)
   386‚Üí
   387‚Üí    In other cases, return the quotient and remainder as `divmod` would do it.
   388‚Üí
   389‚Üí    >>> _quotient_and_remainder(36, 24, Unit.DAYS, Unit.HOURS, [], "%0.2f")
   390‚Üí    (1, 12)
   391‚Üí
   392‚Üí    """
   393‚Üí    if unit == minimum_unit:
   394‚Üí        return _rounding_by_fmt(format, value / divisor), 0
   395‚Üí
